items.title: The Seven Deadly Sins of API Design
items.abstract: There is no doubt that web APIs have become a fundamental aspect of modern architectures. However, how to distinguish a “good” API from an “evil” one is a topic that often ends up in a “religious” debate. However, the one thing that is clear to most people is that it all starts with a design, and getting that design right in the first place will likely translate to fewer headaches down the line. This presentation discusses the seven most common pitfalls this session’s speakers has come across when designing APIs. With real-life examples, he describes why such pitfalls deserve to be called “evil” and how to remediate them with “good" design practices. The presentation is highly interactive, with hands-on demos and examples.

items.title: The Seven Deadly Sins of Software Development
items.abstract: We develop software to make the world a better place. So how do we end up with so much bad software? Bad habits are formed a little at a time. There are seven deadly sins of software development that can kill a project, a team, and our own self-respect. There are also seven good habits—“virtues” if you will—that we can use to write better code and improve the ugly code we work with. Master these virtues, and turn your daily drudgery into a fun daily exercise. Learn more in this session.

items.title: Thread Safety with Phaser, StampedLock, and VarHandle
items.abstract: Every major Java version introduces a new and better way of managing state. Java 7 gave us Phaser as a replacement for CountDownLatch and CyclicBarrier. Hardly any programmers know how it works, even though we are now on Java 11. Java 8 gave us StampedLock, useful as a lighter read “lock” for building concurrent classes. Again not very widely known, but lots of use cases. Java 9/10/11 introduced VarHandle as an escape for Unsafe addicts. This session shows all three concepts and explains when each should be used.

items.title: Three Resilience Patterns Out of the Box with Twitter’s Finagle HTTP Client
items.abstract: Failure is not an option in services that need to be available 24/7. In a service integration environment with a lot of APIs that, in turn, call other APIs or back-end services, there is a lot that can, and inevitably will, go wrong. This session starts by addressing resilience in general. The presenters use devices connected by network cables to physically simulate a working system and use Twitter’s Finagle client for their HTTP connections to overcome some resilience problems of using a low-level HTTP client. Additionally they elaborate on the architecture and philosophy behind Finagle and demonstrate three resilience patterns using the Finagle client.

items.title: Transport Layer Security (TLS) v1.3 support in Java
items.abstract:
The long-awaited Transport Layer Security (TLS) v1.3 is in the last stages of approval by the IETF. This is a major overhaul of the existing TLS 1.2 standard, which provides network communications with authentication, confidentiality (encryption), and message integrity. TLSv1.3’s main benefits include improved security and better performance:
• Modern cryptographic algorithms were added, and obsolete and insecure algorithms such as static RSA, DH, SHA-1, RC4, DES, 3DES, and MD5 were removed.
• Most handshake messages are now encrypted.
• The number of round-trips required during TLS handshaking was reduced.

This session shares details and the current status of the JDK TLS v1.3 implementation.

items.title: Troubleshooting Native Memory Leaks in Java Applications
items.abstract: Apart from the Java heap and the metaspace, which is managed by the JVM, Java processes also allocate in native memory, which is not directly managed by the JVM. From this native memory, thread stacks, loaded JAR/zip files, native libraries, and native resources are allocated. Allocations done from the native code are also made from native memory. Java applications can run into various native-memory issues, including out-of-memory errors or native-memory leaks. This session covers some of the common native-memory issues and how they can be easily spotted. Then it shares some insights into various debugging and troubleshooting tools and the diagnostic data that can help us troubleshoot and nail down native-memory-related issues.

items.title: Tuning G1G
items.abstract: With the release of Java 9, our beloved mostly CMS collector was deprecated and G1GC replaced the parallel collector as the default. The hype surrounding this massive change claims that the G1GC is the best collector…ever. Make no mistake about it: G1GC will be much much easier to tune. So, is this real, or is it #fakenews. This session explores the reality by looking at experiences with moving applications from CMS to G1GC in real production environments. The implications aren’t simply about performance. A suboptimally tuned collector will increase your company’s operating cost by 10% to 20%. The presentation also examines results from benchmarks that expose potential pain points and offers some suggestions on what actions can offer some relief.

items.title: Ultralow Latency with Java 11 and Terabytes of Data
items.abstract: Is it possible to create and consume a standard Java stream in under 200 ns? Just accessing 64-bit main memory takes about 100 ns, and if the stream is backed by huge datasets, high speed becomes less likely. In this session, you will learn how to connect Java streams directly to RAM, enabling retrieval of data with ultralow latency for a wide range of operations. This will work for terabytes of data without affecting garbage collection. The presentation shows how to leverage off-heap memory for storing serialized objects that are accessible via off-heap indexes and elaborates on the recent features in Java 9, 10, and 11 to show how dockerization, added stream operation types, local-variable type inference, and JVM optimizations make the solution easy to use.

items.title: Unknown PL/SQL Code? Use PL/Scope to Gain Control
items.abstract:
Coming into a GDPR-project where you’re supposed to audit, modify, and change code in a totally unknown system with a million lines of code programmed in PL/SQL, might seem daunting. However, with active use of PL/Scope, Oracle’s identifier and statement tracking tool, it is possible to rather easily navigate and identify code that needs to be changed. This session goes through what information is collected by PL/Scope and how it can be utilized. Practical information it collects might include
• Where a table is accessed or modified from
• Where a particular function is used from
• Identification of dead and possibly dead code

The presentation includes some experiments to see if it’s possible make some measurements indicating the quality of the code.

items.title: Var with Style: Local Variable Type Inference in Java
items.abstract: Java 10 introduced a feature called local variable type inference, which enables programmers to declare local variables by using “var” instead of an explicit type. This feature makes it possible to write code that is more concise and more readable. However, it’s also possible for this feature to be misused, obfuscating code instead of making it more readable. The Java team has published a set of style guidelines that help direct programmers toward uses of var that improve code quality and help them avoid uses that detract from code quality. This session presents an overview of the new var feature and describes these style rules. The presentation is liberally supplemented with code examples of good uses as well as misuses of var.

items.title: Visualizing and Analyzing GC Logs with R
items.abstract: GC logs contain very useful information about GC events occurring during the lifetime of our Java applications. This information can provide deep insights into an application’s performance issues. Reading and understanding these GC logs can be very hard and challenging. As we all know, numbers make more sense to the human eye and mind when presented in a graphical format. We can extract useful information from GC logs and plot it in beautiful charts and graphs to understand the GC behavior of our applications. The R language has arrived to help us with that. This session briefly discusses GC logs and extracting useful information from them and delves deeply into the details of how we can visualize and analyze this information with the R language.

items.title: What Is CQRS+Event Sourcing and Why Should Java Developers Care?
items.abstract: Command query responsibility segregation (CQRS) is a design pattern that originates in domain-driven design (DDD) and emphasizes strictly separating reads from updates in the application model. Event sourcing is a closely related technique that stores state as a series of events, as opposed to only keeping track of the latest data. Although these concepts are important in their own right, they are especially important for microservices development. This heavily demo-driven session explores CQRS and event sourcing in detail, using the Axon Java framework and microservices running on Oracle Cloud. At the end of the session, you should have a good idea of whether CQRS and event sourcing are for you and why Axon helps in implementing these concepts.

items.title: What Is Open Data?
items.abstract: Open data has grown from the basic concept of making some data available without charge to all, without restriction, into a movement with guidelines, best practices, governance, and standard access methods to make data not only available but also usable. On a trajectory similar to open source, it’s still a mystery to many. This session unlocks the mysteries of open data so you can better understand what it is, how to find it, how to access it, and how to use it. There are many open data stewards who explicitly define what it means to be open data, and you’ll get ideas on how to find interesting (to you) open data sources and consume them. Since we’re all software engineers, the presentation shows different ways to consume data programatically.

items.title: What Lies Beneath
items.abstract: What really happens when your Java program runs? After the transformation from Java source through bytecode and machine code to microcode, and the various optimizations that take place along the way, the instructions that are actually executed may be very different from what you imagined when you wrote the program. This session shows you tools and techniques for tracing that path. You’ll see what a simple program actually looks like when it really hits the hardware.
